Operation: Defend the Flag (API Key Edition)

Objective

Prove your system can’t be easily abused—even if someone is actively trying.

⸻

1. Threat Model (who’s trying to grab your flag)

Think like an attacker, but stay defensive:
	•	careless dev commits a key
	•	key leaks in logs
	•	frontend accidentally exposes it
	•	someone screenshots config
	•	CI/CD misconfiguration

⸻

2. Common Leak Paths (these are the real weak points)

🔴 #1 — GitHub commits
	•	.env accidentally pushed
	•	config files with keys

🔴 #2 — Frontend exposure
	•	key in JavaScript bundle
	•	anything visible in browser = public

🔴 #3 — Logs
	•	printing keys during debugging

🔴 #4 — Screenshots / docs
	•	sharing dashboards or configs

⸻

3. Build Your “Flag Defense”

✅ Rule 1: Keys never live in code

Use:
	•	environment variables
	•	secret managers

⸻

✅ Rule 2: Separate keys by role
	•	dev key
	•	prod key
	•	limited-scope keys

If one leaks → blast radius small

⸻

✅ Rule 3: Add usage limits
	•	rate limits
	•	budget caps

⸻

✅ Rule 4: Monitor usage

Set alerts for:
	•	spikes
	•	unusual patterns

⸻

✅ Rule 5: Fast rotation protocol

Have a simple rule:

“Leak suspected → rotate immediately”

⸻

4. Turn it into a real “game”

You can run this safely:

Round 1 — Self audit

Try to “break” your own setup:
	•	where could a key leak?

⸻

Round 2 — Simulated leak

Pretend a key is exposed:
	•	how fast can you rotate?
	•	what breaks?

⸻

Round 3 — Hardening

Patch every weak spot you find

⸻

5. Pantheon framing
	•	Sieve (Hogge) → strip exposure paths
	•	Indigo Hammer → stress test your security
	•	Kintsugi → repair weak points visibly
	•	Checksum → ensure integrity holds
	•	ZPC → turn risk into stronger architecture

